detailedRequirements:
Summary

The quick and dirty;

What's needed: Ideas for optimized sampling of environmental data.

What this is: A potentially hard but awesome code ideation challenge with the right answers providing huge benefits to scientific work.

Overview

We're seeking optimised sampling strategies for an environmental measurement in order to identify values greater than or equal to the 90th percentile of the whole dataset.  

Measurements of environmental variables will vary by:

  1. location and

  2. over time at the same location.

We have collected data recording measurements made at many locations over a long period of time (the data-set is available for download via a link on the challenge contest forums)

How could we obtain the best estimate of the 90th percentile measurement of the dataset using one or a mix of the following?

  • Sampling a reduced number of sites or

  • Sampling the same sites over a fixed period of time

  • Sampling sites with variable time intervals (e.g.,  every 3 months or 6 months etc.)

Note: Both static and dynamic (i.e., changing over time) sampling strategies are welcome, with the aim being to reduce the total number of samples taken.

Problem Description

We have a file containing over 30 million environmental measurements made at approximately 125,000 locations over a period of 20 years. Each of these measurements is expensive and consumes scarce resources.  It is not known whether the variation of this measurement over space (i.e., different locations) dominates over variation in time (i.e., at the same location), particularly with respect to extremes in the dataset (i.e.,  the 90th percentile and above or 1.086E-04 for this dataset).  The ultimate aim is to understand whether extremely high values in the dataset are more likely to be measured using a few measurements at many locations or many measurements at a few locations.    

Challenge Objective

We would like to explore different ways of sampling these data to obtain the best estimate of the 90th percentile value for the whole dataset. Different strategies to sample the measurements are desired, so that we can reliably obtain the best estimate if the 90th percentile (values slightly in excess of the 90th centile would be preferred to those below, but values well in excess of the 90th centile are not desirable. This is explained in greater detail below). Your method must:

  • Reliably obtain a good estimate of the 90th percentile of the whole dataset regularly

  • Have a reduced total number of samplings, defined as

where

s(i) = 0 if plot i is not sampled at all or 1 otherwise

t(i) = number of times plot i is sampled

n = total number of plots

Your method could involve a dynamic strategy in which both s(i) and t(i) are varied based on the value of the concentration at or before a time t. Your proposed method must obtain the 90th centile measurement (defined above) reliably (defined as obtaining it between 88-94 percentile values for 20 different runs). You will be required to explain your method using simple English and provide code (C/C++/R/Java/Python) to test out your method, We will test your submission on data you will not have seen. The top 2 methods which pass our criteria as defined above (i.e. reliably produce the 90th percentile values and have the least number of total samplings) will be deemed the winning entries. Entries will have to obtain the extreme values within 88-94 percentile to be considered for a prize. Within this window, an entry will be deemed to be better if it uses the smaller total number of samplings.

Description of the Data:

As mentioned the download link for the data is available through the challenge contest forums in the file CL_OP.csv, which is approximately 327MB in size and contains data on 125,480 different locations in space, termed “plots”.  Each plot has monthly measurements made over a 20 year period ,starting on Jan 1907 and ending on Dec 1927. Measurements are made at the same month in all locations, and there are no data gaps.  The file is organised at the plot level (i.e. each row of the csv file contains the plot-ID and then the sequence of measurements).  The csv header contains the measurement date information in format YYYY - MM. We imagine that this is a solved problem in other fields - please make use of any prior knowledge you have in generating your solutions here! We're hoping you can delight us with your proposals. With that being said please note that independent, new proposals are highly welcome and desired too.
finalSubmissionGuidelines:
Please not the only technology requirements for this challenge:

  1. You must provide any necessary installation guidelines if your solution requires 3rd party libraries (open-source only)
  2. Your solution must be linux-based.
  3. Java/C/C++/Python/R with any open source packages are OK to use. Other languages and packages may be okay too - but please ask and obtain go-ahead first.

All submissions will be evaluated subjectively by the client. Where possible we will provide feedback to submitters with the intent of helping them improve their submissions. We will not share information between submitters and will attempt to be fair in every way. Please use the forum or email kprice@appirio.com, ragu@appirio.com and tkirchner@appirio.com with any questions.
